sentence: Home improvement retailer Home Depot ( HD ) is expected to report its first-quarter results before the market open on May 16, with analysts forecasting earnings of $1.61 per share, up from $1.44 during the same period last year.
HD shares are up 16.8% on the year.
HD was recently trading at $156.90, down $1.25 from its 12-month high and $37.70 above its 12-month low.
Technical indicators for HD are bullish and the stock is in a strong upward trend.
The stock has recent support above $152.50 and has recent resistance below $158.15.
Of the 19 analysts who cover the stock, 10 rate it a "strong buy", two rate it a "buy", and seven rate it a "hold".
The stock receives S&P Capital IQ's 4 STARS "Buy" ranking.
The housing market remains solid, and the home improvement sector has enjoyed steady growth as a result.
HD shares have trended steadily higher over the last six months, and is currently trading just shy of its all-time high.
With the stock near its record high, the valuation has risen to a P/E of 24.3, which is a little high, but considering the company's growth estimates, the valuation is justified.
Analysts see Q1 earnings rising 11.8% year over year, and full year earnings growth of 11.6%.

Home Depot has a good earnings track record, posting better than expected results 17 out of the last 19 quarters, and the two quarters it did not top estimates it posted results that were in-line with the consensus.
Analysts expect another earnings beat, with the street having a whisper number of $1.64, which is three cents above the consensus.
Another earnings beat will propel the stock higher, and push shares to a new record high.
If you are looking for a bullish hedged option trade on HD, consider a September 135/140 bull-put credit spread for a 50-cent credit.
That's a potential 11.1% return (32.2% annualized*) and the stock would have to fall 10.5% to cause a problem.
If you want to take a bearish stance on the stock at this time, consider a September 175/180 bear-call credit spread for a $0.40 credit.
That's a potential 8.7% return (25.2% annualized*) and the stock would have to rise 11.8% to cause a problem.
